# SwiftUI Best Practices (meApp iOS)

## 1. View Structure
- One main View per file (exception: multiple previews allowed).
- Every SwiftUI file must contain at least one preview using `#Preview`.
- Prefer stateless views unless state is required.
- Use `@Observable` for state management.

## 2. State Management
- Use `@StateObject` for ViewModels/Stores.
- Use `@State` for local view state.
- Use `@EnvironmentObject` for global state.
- Use `@FocusState` for focus management.

## 3. Design System Enforcement
- Use only design system resources from `Theme/`.
- Never hardcode colors, fonts, or spacing.
- Use `@Environment(\.appTheme)` for theming.
- Use shared components from `Features/Common/` when available.

## 4. Static String Management
- All static text must be in dedicated `Strings` files.
- Create `Strings/` subfolder in each feature.
- Use PascalCase for string structs and constants.
- Reference static text from corresponding `Strings` object.
- Applies to all views in `Features/` folders.

## 5. Advanced State & Memory Management
- Use `@StateObject` only when the view owns the object lifecycle; use `@ObservedObject` for injected dependencies to avoid retain cycles and memory leaks ([Common Mistakes with @StateObject](https://medium.com/@shahin.cse.sust/common-mistakes-with-stateobject-in-swiftui-how-to-avoid-them-e03e84a2de5f)).
- For shared data, prefer `@EnvironmentObject` but avoid for deeply nested dependencies; use `@Binding` for explicit parent-child state propagation.
- Avoid unnecessary object creation: inject heavy view models as `@ObservedObject` from parent views when possible.

## 6. List & Large Data Performance
- For very large datasets, prefer `List` over `LazyVStack` for better off-screen view management ([Common Complex Issues in SwiftUI](https://medium.com/@authfy/common-complex-issues-in-swiftui-development-and-how-to-fix-them-31539faddad9)).
- Always provide unique, stable identifiers for list items.

## 7. Offloading Heavy Computation
- Never perform heavy computations in the view `body`; use background threads or async tasks and update state on the main thread.
- Use `Task` or `DispatchQueue.global` for background work, and update `@State` on the main thread.

## 8. Value Types & Copy-on-Write
- Prefer value types (struct, enum) for large data models to leverage Swift's copy-on-write optimizations.
- Avoid reference types unless shared mutable state is required.

## 9. Explicit Resource Cleanup
- For heavy resources (media players, large buffers), explicitly release them in `.onDisappear` or via cancellation tokens.
- Use weak references in view models to avoid retain cycles, especially in navigation flows.

## 10. Equatable Views
- Conform views to `Equatable` when possible to help SwiftUI skip unnecessary updates.
- Only use Equatable when you can provide a meaningful and efficient `==` implementation.

## 11. Navigation & View Lifecycle
- Avoid strong references from child to parent view models to prevent memory leaks in navigation flows.
- Use weak references and clean up resources in `.onDisappear`.

---

**Summary:**
- All UI must use SwiftUI, the design system, and externalized strings, with previews and proper state management.
